post_text:
Great News! Jackson14989, from Houston Elementary School, has been selected as a finalist for this week's "Artist of the Week" award for the 4-6 grade age group. The finalist who receives the most online votes between now and Saturday, September 5 will be selected as our "Artist of the Week."

The "Artist of the Week" will be featured on the Artsonia homepage and will receive a commemorative plaque from Artsonia. In addition, Blick Art Materials has generously donated $100 gift certificates to the winning schools and $50 to the winning artists.

We need everyone to vote everyday from any computer/device you have! You can vote at home and at school. We have had winners in the past and it would be exciting to have another!

To view the finalists and cast your vote, simply click on the link below. Voting is limited to one vote per computer per day for each age group!

https://www.artsonia.com/museum/aotw/vote.asp

Thank you for your help!

For the Jv and Varsity Volleyball game in Cuba on Thursday 9/3.
You must have a voucher to be able to pay to get in the game. Spectators are asked to sit in designated areas, in family pods and maintain social distance. Cuba Highly recommends face coverings be worn and the visitors seating will be in the left bleachers when you enter the gym.

For the football game in St. James on Friday 9/4.
You must have a voucher to be able to pay to get in the game. For the spectators who are choosing to sit in the main stadium masks are required and must be worn, If a spectator is on the ground to the sides of the bleachers, and can be socially distanced, they can remove their masks.

Anyone needing a voucher contact Coach Hall at bhall@houston.k12.mo.us..

This is an important message concerning orientations for 6th grade and 9th grade students, as well as new students to the middle school and high school. There will be NO formal, seated orientation this evening. All pertinent information will be given to you via printed copy at the door or by email. Both the middle school and the high school will be open to 6th grade, 9th grade, and new students from 6:00 - 7:30 pm. However, we do ask that you keep the flow of traffic moving. We would like to prevent groups or individuals from lingering too long in one space. Masks are highly encouraged. If you have any questions, please contact your respective building office.

Thank you!

post_text: One of the projects our maintenance crew worked on this summer was the step/entryway on the east side of the Middle school building. Part of this project involved moving the concrete pillars that used to be next to the central office, refurbishing the light poles and putting new globes on. These are connected to a photo cell for night lighting. Thank you to Matt Robertson along with Dave Rust and other staff that helped restore this feature to our school!

Houston Tiger Pride Band
July 11 at 6:02 PM ¬∑

A week from tonight at 5PM, we'll have our first Houston Bands Ice Cream Social outside the doors of Hiett Gymnasium! We want MS & HS band families to join us for a sweet treat, to hear plans for the fall, learn about our 2020 marching show, get some Q&A, fill & collect forms, and pick up music for this coming year! Go Tigers! üêØ

One instance of COVID can sink our ship! Be conscientious by masking up, bringing pocket-sized hand sanitizer, and giving space to our friends who prefer to socially distance.

We will meet outdoors, serve individually packaged treats, use ServSafe principles, and immediately dispose of the trash we collect. Please drop a comment or email svandielen@houston.k12.mo.us with questions or for a digital summary!

To help follow safe practice guidelines before entering the elementary building everyone will need to fill out the form regarding travel. If anyone has traveled outside of the state we will reschedule your screening. We will also be taking temperatures at the door. If you are sick, or appear to be not feeling we will reschedule your screening.

We will have masks available for anyone who wants to wear one. They will not be required.

We will have cleaning solution for all of the teachers who are assessing to disinfect the testing materials in between each student. We do not share testing protocols; each student will have their own.

For any questions please feel free to call the elementary office between 8:00-2:00 417-967-3024

shared_text:
City of Houston Missouri
May 6 at 1:34 PM ¬∑

The City of Houston is proud to announce that in partnership with Joe Ward Photography, and Houston School District we have finally placed a banner of every graduating tiger in our downtown.

We received all of the banners this morning and by this afternoon we were able to place every banner we received. If you notice that there is a senior that is missing please contact us and we will get it placed as soon as possible.

The amount of community spirit that our businesses and residents have is another reason why we love our small town. Without all of you and your continued support, we couldn't have made this possible.

Congrats to the 2020 TIgers we are all very proud of you! Once a Tiger-Always a Tiger!
text:
City of Houston Missouri
May 6 at 1:34 PM ¬∑

The City of Houston is proud to announce that in partnership with Joe Ward Photography, and Houston School District we have finally placed a banner of every graduating tiger in our downtown.

We received all of the banners this morning and by this afternoon we were able to place every banner we received. If you notice that there is a senior that is missing please contact us and we will get it placed as soon as possible.

The amount of community spirit that our businesses and residents have is another reason why we love our small town. Without all of you and your continued support, we couldn't have made this possible.

Congrats to the 2020 TIgers we are all very proud of you! Once a Tiger-Always a Tiger!

5th grade hosted a ZOOM Talent Show where several students showed off their amazing talents. We had dog tricks, Lego creations, tye dying, guitar playing, signing of a song, 4 wheeler tricks, story telling with an English twist, and several students who just showed to support their classmates!

These times have been tough, but the 5th grade team wants to thank our parents for being supportive and sharing their students with us! We love you 5th grade and good luck with your middle school adventure!

Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education
May 1 at 7:00 AM ¬∑

Today, we celebrate "School Lunch Hero Day!" Between preparing healthy food, adhering to strict nutrition standards, navigating student food allergies, and offering service with a smile, Missouri nutrition professionals have a lot on their plate on a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù day. Extended building closures during COVID-19 required our food service professionals to quickly be innovative and creative to develop ways to continue feeding the Missouri students who rely on school breakfast and lunch each day.

Join us in recognizing these important team members today!

We are excited to announce the hanging of all senior banners/flags in downtown Houston! This has been a huge partnership between Houston School, the City of Houston, and Ward Photography (Joe Ward)! Flags will be hung in the next couple of weeks. If you are interested in sponsoring the project, please contact Dr. Justin Copley at jcopley@houston.k12.mo.us. Thank you for your patience as it will take time to hang all flags.

post_text:
Reminder: Friday night lights tonight! Come out and support our seniors by honking your horn and flashing your lights from 8:20-8:40!

BUT WAIT... We have a special pre-game starting at 7:30!

Starting at 7:30, drive by the track, then up to the baseball field, down by the tennis courts, and over to the softball field. The senior athletes will have special items posted along the fence! The senior athletes will also be in their cars/trucks in the respective parking lots practicing social distancing.

Please plan to drive by and honk to show your support.

We encourage everyone to stay in their vehicles as we respect the order set by the governor.

Thanks!

Starting Friday night, April 10, Houston High School will be joining schools around the country in the ‚ÄúBe The Light Campaign.‚Äù We will turn on our football/track, softball, tennis, and baseball stadium lights on Friday nights at 8:20 p.m., which is 20:20 military time, and leaving them lit for 20 minutes to honor the class of 2020. We want all community members to be aware in the event someone is wondering why our stadium lights are on.

At 8:20 p.m. on Friday nights look toward the stadiums to see the glow of our support for our graduating class of 2020.

Also, stay tuned for something special next Friday during this time!

Please, continue to follow CDC guidance and stay safe and healthy. We miss all of our students and staff!

Sincerely,

HHS Administration and Coaches

The MSHSAA Music (Band & Choir) Festivals scheduled for today and tomorrow have been suspended through March 21. Students who traveled to West Plains this morning will be returning to school and those scheduled to travel will remain at school. Please see the MSHSAA Broadcast Email below:

From: Davine Davis, MSHSAA
Date: March 12, 2020
Re: MSHSAA Suspending Music Festivals Due to Coronavirus

Due to concerns for the health and safety of our student performers, spectators, accompanists, directors, adjudicators, and staff, the MSHSAA is suspending all district solo/small ensemble and state large group music festivals through March 21, 2020.

Our office will continue to monitor the situation and determine how best to proceed with the festivals in the upcoming weeks.

Due to concerns for the health and safety of our student performers, spectators, accompanists, directors, adjudicators, and staff, the MSHSAA is suspending all district solo/small ensemble and state large group music festivals through March 21, 2020.

Our office will continue to monitor the situation and determine how best to proceed with the festivals in the upcoming weeks.

Bright Futures Houston
March 9 at 5:14 PM ¬∑

We are asking our community to assist Bright Futures Houston and the Houston R-1 School district with the donation of snack treats to be served to students during MAP and EOC testing. For the remaining month of March and during the month April. We will use our bucket locations to collect the items or people can drop items off at any of the offices at the school.

The list below is not a comprehensive list but it is good for suggestions. If you would like to make a monetary donation for this cause you may contact Glenda Jones at 417-499-3570 or at brightfutureshouston@gmail.com we then would make the purchase of snacks. We are a 501(c)3 charitable organization.

Here are some ideas these should be individually packaged snacks:
Rice Krispy Treats
Granola Bars
Fruit Snacks
Peppermints
Mini Chocolate Bars
Capri Suns
Individual Bags of Chips
Individual Bags of Cookies (i.e. Oreos, Chips A-Hoy, etc.)
Individual Bags of Crackers (i.e. Goldfish, Cheese Its, etc.)
Jolly Ranchers

Good Afternoon,
If you have been on the HS/MS campus the last couple of days, there has been some activity on our building site. Construction fencing is starting to go up and some prep work is being done to begin excavation for our new gym complex.

After our groundbreaking ceremony on Tuesday, the construction zone will be fenced off. This will include the lot just south of the Carter softball field and parking to the north of the gym/band room. Parent pickup and drop off will no longer be available at this area.

While this is an exciting time, please be prepared for the changes to these areas.

post_text: At approximately 9:30 a.m. on 2/28/2020, Houston Middle and High School went into a soft lockdown due to a student issue. Classroom instruction did continue. Students and staff are safe. All students and staff were asked to stay inside classrooms for approximately 5 minutes during the lockdown. The Houston Police Department was dispatched immediately to the high school. Law enforcement has taken a juvenile in for further questioning. Again, our top priority is student safety. All classes have resumed to a normal schedule.

Family and friends are invited to the Melba Performing Arts Center February 23 for the National Honor Society induction ceremony at 3:00 p.m.

Also for the Senior (high school) BETA Club Induction Ceremony Sunday at 3:45 pm. Members will display entries and awards from the state convention. In addition, a parent meeting will be held after the BETA Club ceremony to discuss fundraising and trip ideas for the national convention in June.

post_text:
Congratulations to senior, Jaekan Moss, for being nominated and selected for Academic All-State in football. Students who receive Academic All-State must meet two of the three criteria:

1. Must score a 25 or higher on ACT or 1740 on the SAT
2. 3.5 GPA or higher (GPA must be non weighted)
3. Must rank in top 10% of his/her class

Again, congratulations on a job well-done!

post_text:
Houston School District is so fortunate to have the best of the best when it comes to our school counselors!

They help maximize learning for your students, provide a safe space for conversations and countless resources to students, parents, & co-workers. They are masters of coordinating your student's schedule, and are a constant cheerleader for their success!

Thank you to our school counselors: Maggie Moore, Missy Reed, and Tara Volk - this week's for you! #TheTigerWay
